Smith & Wesson Model 10-7 Revolver, K-Frame, double action, s/n 53323. I have put a lot of time/money/love into this gun and you will not be disappointed.  History: I purchased both of this guns at auction about a year ago with the intention of selling them to make a quick buck. Well... this revolver was a rusty piece of junk when I got it. Originally blued, I sanded the ever loving sh**t out of it with 600 grit sand paper for hours on end, polished the silver/chrome, replaced the main spring, re-finished the wood grips, took the entire gun apart and cleaned/oiled every moving part, etc. Now, this gun shoots more accurately with the 2" barrel than my fathers Colt .38 4.5" barrel. The new main spring gives it a very smooth/light trigger pull, the cylinder spins for days when you turn it, and you will L.O.V.E this gun. It still shows evidence of the rust from improper storage which has left cosmetic defects (blemishes) around the frame of the gun, however, it has been sanded COMPLETELY smooth to the touch.

Star Interarms Alexandria Virginia R-9 Cal. 9mm Parabellum s/n OR 2333. Only shot this gun a few times, typical 9mm pistol, 15 round clip which I really like. When I first shot the gun it jammed quite a bit, however, after a good cleaning, it shoots fine. It does not have the rear sight so it only has the front pin which makes it less accurate (obviously). Just a warning, I personally have found it difficult to find parts for this gun, but I also do not know much about guns in general and don't really know where to look (maybe you will have better luck), so plan on the rear sight being difficult to find or talk to a machinist buddy and try making one. 

My goal here was to be as upfront as possible, these guns are nothing to write home about, but they are a very good deal and you are getting the best of both worlds (38 special 6 shooter revolver AND a 9 mm with a large clip). 2 for the price of 1!

I got this Smith and Wesson 908 a few months ago and finally got around to shooting it today, and now i've realized how uncomfortable it is to shoot for my hands, and want to get rid of it. I have very stiff hands, so when the gun recoils, it almost jumps out of my hand (and I have a VERY strong grip) due to my arm staying in the same place, causing my finger to slam into the bottom of the trigger guard with every shot.  All versions of the GSG 522 has a tactical rail up top that allows you to easily mount red dots, reflex red dots or any size scope you'd like to put up there. The rail is built in so there is no added parts to buy.

 The GSG 522 SD features a rubber ribbed hand guard and larger "SD" barrel shroud. The GSG 522 carbine features a more rigid plastic hand guard and smaller barrel shroud. You can easily remove the front hand guard for cleaning or to put on an after market front hand guard.

postcontent:
Brand New in the Box.

Taurus Security System (TSS)rs
Taurus family of semi-auto pistols all feature the Taurus Security System, which provides instant-ready defense with built-in ability to secure your pistol and make it inoperable at the turn of a key. When the Security System is engaged, the pistol cannot be fired or cocked and the gun's manual safety cannot be disengaged. As with our revolver Security System, the device is part of the firearm and cannot be lost, and the same special Security Key works for both the revolver and pistol Systems (two keys come with most guns). To engage: simply insert the Key into the button on the rear or side of the pistol and rotate one-quarter turn clockwise. This engages the Security System. The manual safety cannot be moved and the trigger cannot be pulled. To disengage: simply rotate the key one-quarter turn back. This releases the Security System, yet leaves the pistol's manual safety in the "safe" position until you are ready to release it yourself and fire the gun. 

   Transfer Bar
The transfer bar mechanism prevents the hammer from striking the firing pin unless the trigger is pulled fully to the rear.
